Use the standard library

This is how to order_by_points of nums:
   Remember that pairs is []
   Remember that i is 0

   Do this nums's length times:
      Remember that n is item i in nums
      Remember that m is abs of n
      Remember that points is 0

      When m is 0, then:
         Remember that points is 0
      But, if not:
         Do this 20 times:
            When m is 0, then:
               Leave the loop
            End when
            Remember that points is sum of points and (remainder of m and 10)
            Remember that m is quotient of m and 10
         End do
      End when

      Add pairs to {"n": n, "points": points}
      Increase i
   End do

   Remember that result is []
   Remember that used is []

   Remember that j is 0
   Do this pairs's length times:
      Add used to no
   End do

   Remember that count is 0
   Do this pairs's length times:
      Remember that best_index is -1
      Remember that best_points is 0
      Remember that best_value is 0

      Remember that k is 0
      Do this pairs's length times:
         When item k in used is no, then:
            Remember that candidate is item k in pairs
            Remember that candidate_points is item "points" in candidate
            Remember that candidate_value is item "n" in candidate

            When best_index is -1, then:
               Remember that best_index is k
               Remember that best_points is candidate_points
               Remember that best_value is candidate_value
            But, if not:
               When candidate_points is less than best_points, then:
                  Remember that best_index is k
                  Remember that best_points is candidate_points
                  Remember that best_value is candidate_value
               But, if not:
                  When candidate_points is best_points, then:
                     When candidate_value is less than best_value, then:
                        Remember that best_index is k
                        Remember that best_points is candidate_points
                        Remember that best_value is candidate_value
                     End when
                  End when
               End when
            End when
         End when
         Increase k
      End do

      Remember that item best_index in used is yes
      Add result to best_value
      Increase count
   End do

   The answer is result
Now you know

>>> order_by_points of [1, 11, -1, -11, -12]
[-1, -11, 1, -12, 11]
>>> order_by_points of [1, 11, -1, -11, -12]
[-1, -11, 1, -12, 11]
>>> order_by_points of [1234, 423, 463, 145, 2, 423, 423, 53, 6, 37, 3457, 3, 56, 0, 46]
[0, 2, 3, 6, 53, 423, 423, 423, 1234, 145, 37, 46, 56, 463, 3457]